mp4 by the menu. Other app's use a lot of software resource to construct

For people in the business this might seem obvious,however,for the others, this will be helpful to know. Need to set the camera(s) up on the wifi router using WPS connection in order to get the IP address, to setup the camera, with the IP Camera Viewer app. 1.Find your wifi routers setup menu using your browser. 2.Most IP cameras have a reset button, hold it, 5 sec. 3.Press the WPS button on your router. 4.Find IP camera address connected in the router menu.5.Transcribe the IP to the IP camera viewer app.

The application also seems to be quick and reliable.  A few room for improvement items: 1) GUI - I know we have come to accept unattractive GUI's with odd menu systems on IP Camera software, and this is no different. Updating the GUI with a better drop down menu, one that is in line with material design in function and appearance would be a great addition.   2) Audio Options - As of now there is no advanced settings for audio. Playback and talk work, but additional settings like an audio boost feature would go a long way.

I don't normally review or rave about apps, but in this case : this is unbelievably reliable and responsive app, and has a vast selection of different camera brands & models to select from. I had no difficulty setting up my 6 different models of 3 different brands ... 10 cameras in total. Both video & audio is very responsive when switching between cameras. Finally an app that pulls them cleanly & consistently together in one place (I don't know how long it has been available, but I just found it).   Before this app, over previous years I got used using a patchwork of browsers & rtsp players that took forever to connect (different setups depending on the camera and the platform) to get sub-standard or no results on my various cameras. Some only worked well on old versions of internet explorer. Some only played in an rstp player. Some I couldn't view video at all and just made do with still image snapshots. I even used to resorted to viewing some on my android via a remote desktop to my home PC!. Now all of them are there with full sound & video at any time.  Definitely 5+ stars!  Hope there will be a windows version one day! (and I don't mean windows mobile...)

If you only want Wifi access to camera, then first verify network accessibility by viewing your camera/dvr's login page using the phone/tablet browser.

If you want 2/3/4g access to camera, then verify network setup by viewing your camera/dvr using a PC IE browser from OUTSIDE your home wifi.
